00:16:17.599 --> 00:16:24.239
All right. One of the first things I implemented when I started on the project

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:35.200
was the observable JavaScript integration. So, this is a little on the wonky programming side

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:44.400
for folks who are not deep in it. But there's a separate company, actually, that builds an

00:16:44.400 --> 00:16:51.359
open source product called observable JavaScript, which is a way to make your web pages, make it

00:16:51.359 --> 00:16:59.280
very easy to write web pages with interactive content in a way that is very close to what Shiny

00:16:59.280 --> 00:17:04.239
does. But instead of writing R code, you write JavaScript. So, it's kind of like a reactive

00:17:04.239 --> 00:17:10.719
JavaScript thing, which is really great if you want to write sort of fast interactive content

00:17:10.719 --> 00:17:17.760
that doesn't need to sort of talk back to a server as often in R. And one of my really favorite

00:17:17.760 --> 00:17:24.319
things that I think is actually underutilized is that in Quarto, the R reactives that you get from

00:17:24.319 --> 00:17:29.439
Shiny. So, if you're using Quarto to build a Shiny app, which you can do. So, you can actually

00:17:29.439 --> 00:17:35.760
have Quarto generate from a single markdown page, both the UI and the server page to get real Shiny

00:17:35.760 --> 00:17:43.920
applications going. If that page has observable reactives, they both work together transparently.

00:17:43.920 --> 00:17:50.079
So, from R, you can refer to the JavaScript observables to get sort of JavaScript values. And

00:17:50.079 --> 00:17:56.959
from JavaScript reactives, you can refer to Shiny reactives. And they both work reactively and know

00:17:56.959 --> 00:18:01.280
what parts go on the server and what parts go on the client. So, if you can do both of those things,

00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:09.119
they just work transparently with each other, which is quite nice because observable has a huge

00:18:09.119 --> 00:18:15.760
library of JavaScript observables that is sort of quite different from the Shiny thing. So,

00:18:15.760 --> 00:18:22.319
if you find one piece of observable JavaScript, you can just directly import it and use it from

00:18:22.319 --> 00:18:26.880
anywhere on the web, and it just works. And then you can sort of reuse them within your Shiny

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:31.599
dashboard. So, it's a way to get your Shiny dashboards to do something that's quite sophisticated

00:18:31.599 --> 00:18:36.160
with JavaScript, and it feels sort of native and nice. And so, we have documentation on that,

00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:42.880
